statement.p:
Suppose that
A=\begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp 2\\
2 \amp 1
\end{bmatrix}
.  If we write \xvec=\twovec{x_1}{x_2}, then we have


    q\left(\twovec {x_1}{x_2}\right) \amp = \twovec
    {x_1}{x_2} \cdot
    \left(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    1 \amp 2 \\
    2 \amp 1
    \end{bmatrix}
    \twovec {x_1}{x_2}
    \right)


    \amp = \twovec {x_1}{x_2} \cdot
    \twovec{x_1 + 2x_2}{2x_1 + x_2}


    \amp = x_1^2 + 2x_1x_2 + 2x_1x_2 + x_2^2


    \amp = x_1^2 + 4x_1x_2 + x_2^2.

We may evaluate the quadratic form using some input vectors:

  q\left(\twovec 10\right) = 1, \hspace{24pt}
  q\left(\twovec 11\right) = 6, \hspace{24pt}
  q\left(\twovec 24\right) = 52.

Notice that the value of the quadratic form is a scalar.

Consider the symmetric matrix A=\begin{bmatrix} -7 \amp -6 \\ -6 \amp 2 \\ \end{bmatrix}. Because A is symmetric, we know that it can be orthogonally diagonalized. In fact, we have A=QDQ^T where
D = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -10 \\ \end{bmatrix},\hspace{24pt} Q = \begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{5} \amp 2/\sqrt{5} \\ -2/\sqrt{5} \amp 1/\sqrt{5} \\ \end{bmatrix}\text{.}
From this diagonalization, we know that \lambda_1=5 is the largest eigenvalue of A with associated eigenvector \uvec_1 = \twovec{1/\sqrt{5}}{-2/\sqrt{5}} and that \lambda_2 = -10 is the smallest eigenvalue with associated eigenvector \uvec_2 = \twovec{2/\sqrt{5}}{1/\sqrt{5}}.

Let's first study the quadratic form q_D(\uvec) = 5u_1^2 - 10u_2^2 because the absence of the cross-term makes it comparatively simple. Remembering that \uvec is a unit vector, we have u_1^2+u_2^2=1, which means that u_1^2 = 1-u_2^2. Therefore,
q_D(\uvec) = 5u_1^2 - 10u_2^2 = 5(1-u_2^2)-10u_2^2 = 5 - 15u_2^2\text{.}
This tells us that q_D(\uvec) has a maximum value of 5, which occurs when u_2=0 or in the direction \twovec10.

Let's now return to the matrix A whose quadratic form q_A is related to q_D because A = QDQ^T. In particular, we have
q_A(\uvec) = \uvec\cdot(A\uvec) = \uvec\cdot(QDQ^T\uvec) = (Q^T\uvec)\cdot(DQ^T\uvec) = \vvec\cdot(D\vvec) = q_D(\vvec)\text{.}
In other words, we have q_A(\uvec) = q_D(\vvec) where \vvec=Q^T\uvec. This is quite useful because it allows us to relate the values of q_A to those of q_D, which we already understand quite well.

Suppose that A is the symmetric matrix A=\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 6 \amp 3 \\ 6 \amp 3 \amp 6 \\ 0 \amp 6 \amp 6 \\ \end{bmatrix}, which may be orthogonally diagonalized as A=QDQ^T where
D = \begin{bmatrix} 12 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -6 \\ \end{bmatrix}, \hspace{24pt} Q = \begin{bmatrix} 1/3 \amp 2/3 \amp 2/3 \\ 2/3 \amp 1/3 \amp -2/3 \\ 2/3 \amp -2/3 \amp 1/3 \\ \end{bmatrix}\text{.}
We see that the maximum value of q_A(\uvec) is 12, which occurs in the direction \threevec{1/3}{2/3}{2/3}, and the minimum value is -6, which occurs in the direction \threevec{2/3}{-2/3}{1/3}.

li.p:
We have

  f_{xx} = 12x, \hspace{24pt}
  f_{xy} = -6, \hspace{24pt}
  f_{yy} = 6

The matrix is A = \begin{bmatrix}
6 \amp -3 \\
-3 \amp 3
\end{bmatrix}
.

We have

  f_{xx} = 12x, \hspace{24pt}
  f_{xy} = -6, \hspace{24pt}
  f_{yy} = 6

A = \begin{bmatrix}
6 \amp -3 \\
-3 \amp 3
\end{bmatrix}
.

subsection.p:
The matrix
H = \begin{bmatrix} f_{xx}(x_0,y_0) \amp f_{xy}(x_0,y_0) \\ f_{yx}(x_0,y_0) \amp f_{yy}(x_0,y_0) \end{bmatrix}
is called the Hessian of f, and we see now that the eigenvalues of this symmetric matrix determine the nature of the critical point (x_0,y_0). In particular, if the eigenvalues are both positive, then q_H is positive definite, and the critical point is a local minimum.
